Pre behav expl: I work hard, physically .. avocationally on my hobby farm .. and mentally/i.e. psychologically at my vocation, There are times that I crave various foods depending on the day, the fatigue and the ongoing or upcoming labor that day. I would seriously be at a loss, physically and emotionally if I limited my options, my choice of foods depending on vravings and needs for peak performance as well as reward for jobs well done. Nutrition also plays a role, I am a believer in a well balanced diet and can't see strict limits on selection.
message reaction: I fully understand the point of the above description, however, I also question the efficacy of replacing well designed and high quality animal farming as a way to prevent pandemics. Sure, COVID-19 as well as other diseases might very well have originated in "wet market" environments (rare locales) .. but that doesn't mean all poultry or meat production facilities such as those in Iowa or other states are necessarily disease producing micro-environments. I have worked in fruit and timber and agricultural production and some of the chemicals used producing non-organic produce are hazardous enough that they frightened me .. as a professional (produce) producer during their handling and applications.
Beh_intention_reason: I have lived and worked in agriculture since my high school years. I paid my way through five years of college by producing agricultural commodities during summers and vacations to pay my tuition. Yes, I found profitable jobs during my school years .. all "ag" based. Knowing what I know, and having seen what I've witnessed .. I am more than happy to phase into organic-type and shelf stable style products if they can replace various components of my current dietary choices and needs.
Beh_intentio_reason2: My family members have also studied and worked in the biological and agricultural sciences .. my Father has a masters degree in Plant Biology with a specialty in Aquatic Limnology .. my own majors .. my areas in college were microbiology and organic chemistry so my family is well versed in choices and options. I might encourage them by my actions, however, with their backgrounds .. it would be difficult to change their minds using scientific terms.

message reaction: I was surprised to read that piglets who aren't growing fast enough "are brutally killed". I'm not sure I want to know how. My ex-husband worked at a pig farm in NC. I read in some of his training notes that if a sow had not had piglets by a certain date, the sow was killed to remove the piglets. That actually made me ill. I don't know if that was unique to this farm (Murphy Family Farms) or if that is normal practice. I hate thinking about it.

Beh_intentio_reason2: I would want to try them because they are healthier (at least, I think they are). They have fewer calories. I would feel like I wasn't supporting inhumane practices. But what happens to all the animals that aren't used for human consumption? It seems like I read about animals being killed because farmers couldn't get them to the market when COVID first started? I don't know what the perfect solution is.

Pre behav expl: I do not eat a huge amount of meat. I eat mostly poultry (chicken or turkey), occasionally fish, and very occasionally red meat. If I were to reduce the amount of meat in my diet, it would be because the meat industry is not sustainable as it is currently operated. Cattle consume a lot of feed. I would not change my meat-eating habits for health, because I don't think the amount or type of meat I eat is bad for me. message reaction: I'm concerned about the emotionally manipulative language, that plays on guilt. This is not uncommon in animal rights organizations, because the issue itself is highly emotional. But I think that when writing for the public, an organization should do their best to refrain from using that kind of language.
Beh_intention_reason: I've eaten things like soy cheese, and it tastes terrible. I'm not against the idea of eating meat alternatives, because my experience with those are better. Vegetarian Chinese restaurants are very good at this. I drink almond milk in things like oatmeal, or just as a drink to have with a meal. But in coffee or tea, I haven't found a satisfying replacement for milk or half&half, so I continue to buy that. Taste is my main reason for making these decisions.
Beh_intentio_reason2: My friends are exposed to the same sets of arguments and information about vegetarianism/veganism and the meat industry that I am, so I don't think I need to be their source of information. I hate being nagged about my personal choices, so I try not to do that to others.
